    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-12T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-12T06:00:00-05:00" n="782"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d782">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/1708</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Willard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Sebastian</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-12T12:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 12, 1918, noon</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received September 13, 6.50
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1808. Referring again to Department’s 1504, September 3, 2 p.m., Embassy is
                    strongly of opinion that War Trade Board should promptly license for exportation
                    to Spain, in exact accordance with terms of agreement of March 7, 1918, all
                    articles included in said agreement, especially cotton and petroleum, and that
                    any pressure, if and when considered to be advisable, should be brought to bear
                    only through the application of War Trade Board regulation No. 1 in regard to
                    bunkerage. There is neither moral nor legal objection to the application of this
                    regulation after reasonable notification. Reference is here made to first
                    sentence Embassy’s 1776, September 5, 1 p.m.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Willard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
